      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the elusive goblins of extra costs! There are indeed a few sneaky ones that can keep your balance higher than expected. Here are the main ones:\n\n1. Late Fees: If you miss a payment, the loan servicer might slap on a late fee, which can quickly add to your balance.\n\n2. Penalties: Some loans have penalties for early repayment or for missing certain conditions, which can also increase your balance.\n\n3. Origination Fees: When you first took out the loan, there might have been an origination fee, which is a one-time fee charged by the lender for processing your loan.\n\n4. Interest Capitalization: If you have a variable-rate loan or if you make a payment that's less than the interest due, the unpaid interest may be added to the principal, increasing the balance.\n\n5. Administrative Fees: Some loans have administrative fees for things like loan consolidation or refinancing.\n\n6. Insurance: If you have loan insurance, like federal student loan insurance, the premiums can add to your balance.\n\n7. Taxes: If you're a private loan, you might have to pay taxes on the interest, which can increase your balance.\n\nRemember, it's important to read the fine print of your loan agreement to understand all",
